Rating: 3
Never made it before so them mousse took me forever to thicken up..I ended up letting the metal bowl heat up in the hot water and I was on my way with no problem. I wasted way too much time whisking it up without getting the bowl in the simmering water. It came out great. I don't think it really needed the extra dab of whipped cream on the top or the large strawberry for a garnish..mint would have been enough..seemed to be overkill. Would def. do again because it was a nice and attractive desert that I could make ahead.

Rating: 2
This recipe was very different and exciting to the pallate. The mousse tasted a little off, which I suspect was due to poor lemon quality. I would definetly suggest spending a little more to the best quality lemons you can. I think if I had better ones the dessert would have been perfect. I used peaches and strawberries instead of the other fruit as it was all I had on hand. It was great (the peach/lemon combo is one you wouldn't think of, but the syrupy sweetness of the peaches goes marvelously with the tart lemon). Also PLEASE DO THE FOLLOWING- it makes the dessert look EXCEPTIONAL. In a food processor, combine about 1 tablespoon sugar and 1/2 - 3/4 cup of additional berries. Process for about 1 minute to make a fine syrup. Drop a couple drops of the syrup in a staggered pattern on the top of the the mousse. Take a toothpick and gently swirl the syrup (don't overdo it). This creates an absolutely beautiful marbelized top and it takes about 2 minutes to do. Have your guests put their own whipped cream on top so they can appreciate the beautiful design (PLEASE TRY IT! IT LOOKS SO GREAT!!!!)

